# Presentation Slide Rules

## Generation workflow

The user drops the paper into `Paper_files/` and asks you to generate the
slides. You do everything else. Run these steps in order:

0. **Set up `.venv` (first thing, every time).** If `.venv/` does not
   already exist at the repo root, create it and install the Python
   dependencies:

   ```bash
   python3 -m venv .venv
   . .venv/bin/activate
   pip install -r requirements.txt
   ```

   If `.venv/` already exists, just activate it. Every subsequent `python`
   / `pip` call in this workflow must run inside this venv.

1. **Read the paper.** Inventory `Paper_files/`. The paper PDF is the
   source of truth for both content and figures; read it (and any
   accompanying `.tex` / `.bib` / supplementary) to understand the
   structure, claims, and which figures matter for the talk.

2. **Put the figures you will use into `Extracted_figures/`.** Use
   PyMuPDF (`fitz`) to pull embedded images / figure regions out of the
   paper PDF and save them as `Extracted_figures/<descriptive_name>.png`
   (e.g. `architecture.png`, `results_table.png`). If the user also
   dropped pre-extracted figure files into `Paper_files/`, copy those
   into `Extracted_figures/` too. Do not ask the user to extract
   figures; that's your job.

3. **Edit `presentation.tex`.** Update title / author / date and fill the
   body frames. Every frame must end with `\note{...}` on the line
   immediately after `\end{frame}`. Reference every figure as
   `\includegraphics{<basename>}` with **no** path prefix and **no**
   extension.

4. **Compile the PDF.**

   ```bash
   latexmk -pdf -interaction=nonstopmode presentation.tex
   ```

5. **Build the PPTX.**

   ```bash
   python3 beamer_to_pptx.py presentation.tex
   ```

   Always recompile the PDF (step 4) **before** rebuilding the PPTX
   (step 5): the converter uses the PDF for high-fidelity TikZ / table
   cropping.

6. **Self-check against the rules in this file.** Before reporting
   "done" to the user, run the quick verification pass below. Fix
   anything that fails, then recompile (step 4) and rebuild (step 5)
   as needed.

## Post-generation verification

After step 5, confirm all of the following. If any check fails, fix
the `.tex`, rerun steps 4-5, and re-check. Only then tell the user
the deck is ready.

1. **Outputs exist.** `presentation.pdf` and `presentation_editable.pptx`
   are on disk at the repo root (verify with `ls`, not `Glob`).
2. **Every figure reference resolves.** For each `\includegraphics{name}`
   in `presentation.tex`, confirm `Extracted_figures/name.{png,jpg,pdf}`
   exists on disk. Use `ls Extracted_figures/` (not `Glob`).
3. **Every frame has a `\note{...}`** on the line right after
   `\end{frame}`. Grep for `\end{frame}` and eyeball the next line.
4. **No em dashes.** `grep -n -- '---' presentation.tex` should return
   nothing outside `%` comments.
5. **Bold is label-only.** `\textbf{...}` should appear only at the
   start of a bullet, never mid-sentence.
6. **No wide text-only slides.** Any frame without a figure must either
   constrain its text column (`minipage` / single-column `columns`
   ~0.65-0.70\textwidth) or pair bullets with a figure, or be split.
   No edge-to-edge bullet lists on otherwise empty slides.
7. **No dumped dense tables.** Any table with many rows / columns /
   long numbers must be summarized, trimmed to key rows, or split
   across slides; full details belong in `\note{...}`.
8. **Build cleanliness.** `latexmk` finished without errors;
   `beamer_to_pptx.py` ran without raising; the PPTX opens and each
   slide has content.

Report the result briefly to the user: "Generated N slides, verified
against rules 1-8." If any rule was relaxed deliberately (e.g., the
paper genuinely has a two-cell table worth dumping), say so explicitly.

## Verify files with the shell, not just `Glob`

`Glob` and `Grep` respect `.gitignore` / `.cursorignore`, so a file that
exists on disk (especially a large binary like a JPEG / PNG / PDF under
`Paper_files/`) may return zero matches. Before concluding a figure is
missing, confirm with `ls` / `find` in the shell. The shell is ground
truth; editor search is filtered. If a file shows up in `ls` but not in
`Glob`, look for an ignore rule that's hiding it, don't treat the empty
search result as "file doesn't exist."

## The only figure rule

Before you write `\includegraphics{name}` anywhere in `presentation.tex`,
make sure a file `Extracted_figures/name.png` (or `.jpg` / `.pdf`) exists.
If it doesn't, create it in step 2. No other folder matters for figures;
don't reason about search paths, don't reference `Paper_files/<name>`,
don't prefix with `Extracted_figures/`. Just the basename.

(`\graphicspath` and the converter's copy-in behavior exist as a safety
net for edge cases; the agent should not depend on them.)

## Formatting

- **Bold as leading labels only**: `\textbf{Label}:` at the start of
  bullets. Never bold mid-sentence.
- **Consistent bold**: If one bullet on a slide has a bold label, all
  bullets on that slide should.
- **No em dashes** (`---`). Use commas, semicolons, or colons.

## Content

- **Tight bullets.** Each body `\item` must be short (one line on 16:9
  when possible). Put paragraphs of detail in `\note{...}` or split into
  sub-bullets.
- **Sub-bullets for multi-part points**, not one long sentence.
- **Speaker notes on every frame**, on the line right after
  `\end{frame}`. The converter reads these into the PPTX Notes pane.
- **Explain abbreviations in `\note{...}`** on first use (e.g., "CNN
  (Convolutional Neural Network)").
- **Soften absolute language** (e.g., "do not target" over "none
  target").
- **Lead with the top result** on results slides, not baselines.
- **Include key variable comparisons** on results slides where relevant
  (e.g., frame rate differences).
- **Omit distracting outliers** that don't support the main message.

## Layout

- **Image beside text**: `\begin{columns}[T]` with left ~0.50\textwidth
  (text) and right ~0.47\textwidth (figure). Do not place figures below
  text.
- **Text-only slides must not span full width.** If a slide has no
  figure, bullets running edge-to-edge leave the lower half of a 16:9
  page empty and look sparse. Do one of the following instead:
  1. Constrain the bullet column to ~0.65-0.70\textwidth (wrap in a
     `minipage` or a single-column `columns` block) so the text block
     feels intentional, not stranded.
  2. Pair the bullets with a relevant figure from `Extracted_figures/`
     in a `columns` layout (preferred when a figure genuinely supports
     the point).
  3. Split the bullets across two slides so each one has enough
     content to fill vertical space.
  Never leave a wide, short bullet list floating at the top of an
  otherwise empty slide.
- **Text above footer**: `\vspace{-0.4em}` at frame start; cap figure
  height (e.g. `height=0.58\textheight`); use `{\small ...}` for dense
  slides.

## Style

- **Sub-bullet color**: all bullet levels use the same accent color;
  override Beamer defaults if needed.
- **Logo default**: `\renewcommand{\mylogo}{...}` uncommented, pointing
  to `Assets/logo.jpg`. Prefer JPG for the footer logo.
- **Slide titles**: descriptive and audience-friendly (e.g., "Situation
  recognition" over "Factor prediction").

## Tables and TikZ

- The converter rasterizes `\begin{tabular}` and `\begin{tikzpicture}`,
  clipping to the element's own vector/image bbox (booktabs rule lines,
  TikZ paths) rather than whitespace heuristics.
- When a table shares a slide with bullet text, the converter snaps the
  crop to the table's bottom rule line. Do not put explanatory prose
  immediately under such a table; put it in `\note{...}` or on a
  separate frame.
- **Small tables go on the slide as-is.** If the paper's table has a
  handful of rows and columns and stays legible at slide scale (roughly
  up to ~5 rows x ~5 cols of short numbers), reproduce it directly.
- **Large / dense tables must not be dumped onto the slide.** Tables
  with many rows, many columns, or long numbers become unreadable when
  shrunk to slide size. Do one of the following instead:
  1. **Summarize the trend** in 2-3 bullets (e.g., "Model X beats
     baseline by +4.1 mAP across all input sizes; gap widens at low
     resolution") and move the full table to `\note{...}`.
  2. **Show only the most important rows** (best-performing model,
     chosen baseline, and the row that illustrates the key trade-off),
     omitting the rest. Mention in `\note{...}` that the full table is
     in the paper.
  3. **Split** the table by metric or by row group across two slides
     if every row genuinely matters.
  The slide should answer "what should the audience take away?", not
  "here is every number we reported."
